{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17480059","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17480059"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T23:36:29+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T23:36:29+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"8"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"8","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/8"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.53,0.15,0.13,0.07,0.13]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"109972"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"8"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"92331"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"5"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1914"},{"type":"tags","id":"4964"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4992"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11642"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"31568"},{"type":"contributions","id":"31569"},{"type":"contributions","id":"37209"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43774"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"109972","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/109972"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 45-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department with a two week history of fevers and worsening, generalised and constant abdominal pain. His medical history includes untreated Hepatitis C virus.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination he is drowsy and has a musty smell to his breath. His blood pressure is 110/70 mmHg, pulse 100/min and temperature 37.6C. His abdomen is uniformly distended, with widespread tenderness to light palpation and shifting dullness. A diagnostic paracentesis reveals 375 neutrophils/\u00b5L and is sent for culture.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Intravenous ceftriaxone","Intravenous metronidazole","Oral lactulose","Oral sofosbuvir and ribavirin","Therapeutic paracentesis"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EPatients with frank ascites, or those with cirrhotic liver disease at risk of ascites, should be managed with a high index of suspicion for spontaneous bacterial peritonitis (SBP) when presenting with abdominal pain or tenderness, fever, hypotension, or altered mental status. The diagnosis is all but confirmed by the presence of \u0026gt;250 neutrophils/\u00b5L in the ascitic aspirate, though the final definitive step is culturing a pathogenic organism. The working diagnosis in this case is SBP on a background of cirrhosis secondary to Hepatitis C infection. \u003Cbr /\u003E\u003Cbr /\u003ESBP is most commonly caused by \u003Cem\u003EEnterobacteriaceae\u003C/em\u003E (\u003Cem\u003EE. coli\u003C/em\u003E and \u003Cem\u003EKlebsiella\u003C/em\u003E spp. comprising the majority of cases) or \u003Cem\u003EStreptococci\u003C/em\u003E. Therefore, an agent with broad-spectrum coverage including activity against both Gram negative and positive organisms is ideal; the third-generation cephalosporins are generally favoured for the empiric treatment of SBP, with \u003Cstrong\u003Eceftriaxone\u003C/strong\u003E or cefotaxime as first-line in most guidelines.\u003Cbr /\u003E\u003Cbr /\u003EWhilst the combination of \u003Cstrong\u003Esofosbuvir and ribavirin\u003C/strong\u003E is among the current first-line treatments for Hepatitis C based on genotype, the priority in this case is the spontaneous bacterial peritonitis. \u003Cstrong\u003ELactulose\u003C/strong\u003E might be indicated for encephalopathy, but the patient\u0027s drowsiness alone is insufficient to raise significant concern for this. A \u003Cstrong\u003Etherapeutic paracentesis\u003C/strong\u003E might be helpful, but would not treat the underlying infection. \u003Cstrong\u003EMetronidazole\u003C/strong\u003E does not provide appropriate antibiotic cover; anaerobic organisms are rare in SBP due to the high partial pressure of oxygen in ascitic fluid.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Patients with frank ascites, or those with cirrhotic liver disease at risk of ascites, should be managed with a high index of suspicion for spontaneous bacterial peritonitis (SBP) when presenting with abdominal pain or tenderness, fever, hypotension, or altered mental status."],"references":["Dever JB, Sheikh MY. Review article: spontaneous bacterial peritonitis--bacteriology, diagnosis, treatment, risk factors and prevention. Aliment Pharmacol Ther. 2015 Jun;41(11):1116-31. doi: 10.1111/apt.13172. Epub 2015 Mar 26. PMID: 25819304. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/25819304/","Medscape, 2017 Spontaneous Bacterial Peritonitis (SBP) Treatment and ManagementCampoverde\u2011Espinoza CA, Santana\u2011Vargas D, Tovar\u2011Dur\u00e1n A, Govea\u2011Mendoza B, P\u00e9rez\u2011P\u00e9rez VG, Higuera\u2011De\u202fla\u202fTijera F, P\u00e9rez\u2011Hern\u00e1ndez JL. Ceftriaxone versus cefotaxime in the treatment of spontaneous bacterial peritonitis. Ann Hepatol. 2025;30(Suppl\u202f1):Abstract S1665268125000870. doi:\u202f10.1016/j.aohep.2025.101863 Available from: https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S1665268125000870","Electronic Therapeutic Guidelines, 2017 Spontaneous Bacterial Peritonitis","Zhang G, Jazwinski Faust A. Spontaneous Bacterial Peritonitis. JAMA. 2021;325(11):1118. doi:10.1001/jama.2020.10292 Available from: https://jamanetwork.com/journals/jama/fullarticle/2777471"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"92331"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"8"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"92331","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/92331"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-07-27T18:55:38+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-07-27T18:55:39+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"109972"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"5","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/5"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2d","name":"Gastroenterology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"76","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/76"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level II","synonyms":null,"description":"Understand (interpreting and summarizing information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"d